[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] This text is a brief description of the features that are present in the Bash shell (version 5.3, 18 May 2025).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The Bash home page is http://www.gnu.org/software/bash/.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] This is Edition 5.3, last updated 18 May 2025, of *The GNU Bash Reference Manual*, for `Bash`, Version 5.3.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Bash contains features that appear in other popular shells, and some features that only appear in Bash.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Some of the shells that Bash has borrowed concepts from are the Bourne Shell (sh), the Korn Shell (ksh), and the C-shell (csh and its successor, tcsh).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The following menu breaks the features up into categories, noting which features were inspired by other shells and which are specific to Bash.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] This manual is meant as a brief introduction to features found in Bash.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The Bash manual page should be used as the definitive reference on shell behavior.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Bash is the shell, or command language interpreter, for the GNU operating system.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The name is an acronym for the ‘Bourne-Again SHell’, a pun on Stephen Bourne, the author of the direct ancestor of the current Unix shell `sh`, which appeared in the Seventh Edition Bell Labs Research version of Unix.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Bash is largely compatible with `sh` and incorporates useful features from the Korn shell `ksh` and the C shell `csh`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] It is intended to be a conformant implementation of the IEEE POSIX Shell and Tools portion of the IEEE POSIX specification (IEEE Standard 1003.1).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] It offers functional improvements over `sh` for both interactive and programming use.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] While the GNU operating system provides other shells, including a version of `csh`, Bash is the default shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Like other GNU software, Bash is quite portable.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] It currently runs on nearly every version of Unix and a few other operating systems − independently-supported ports exist for Windows and other platforms.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] At its base, a shell is simply a macro processor that executes commands.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The term macro processor means functionality where text and symbols are expanded to create larger expressions.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A Unix shell is both a command interpreter and a programming language.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] As a command interpreter, the shell provides the user interface to the rich set of GNU utilities.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The programming language features allow these utilities to be combined.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Users can create files containing commands, and these become commands themselves.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] These new commands have the same status as system commands in directories such as /bin, allowing users or groups to establish custom environments to automate their common tasks.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Shells may be used interactively or non-interactively.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] In interactive mode, they accept input typed from the keyboard.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] When executing non-interactively, shells execute commands read from a file or a string.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A shell allows execution of GNU commands, both synchronously and asynchronously.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The shell waits for synchronous commands to complete before accepting more input; asynchronous commands continue to execute in parallel with the shell while it reads and executes additional commands.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The *redirection* constructs permit fine-grained control of the input and output of those commands.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Moreover, the shell allows control over the contents of commands’ environments.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Shells also provide a small set of built-in commands (*builtins*) implementing functionality impossible or inconvenient to obtain via separate utilities.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] For example, `cd`, `break`, `continue`, and `exec` cannot be implemented outside of the shell because they directly manipulate the shell itself.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The `history`, `getopts`, `kill`, or `pwd` builtins, among others, could be implemented in separate utilities, but they are more convenient to use as builtin commands.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] All of the shell builtins are described in subsequent sections.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] While executing commands is essential, most of the power (and complexity) of shells is due to their embedded programming languages.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Like any high-level language, the shell provides variables, flow control constructs, quoting, and functions.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Shells offer features geared specifically for interactive use rather than to augment the programming language.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] These interactive features include job control, command line editing, command history and aliases.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] This manual describes how Bash provides all of these features.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] These definitions are used throughout the remainder of this manual.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A family of open system standards based on Unix.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Bash is primarily concerned with the Shell and Utilities portion of the POSIX 1003.1 standard.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A character belonging to the `space` character class in the current locale, or for which `isspace()` returns true.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A command that is implemented internally by the shell itself, rather than by an executable program somewhere in the file system.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A `token` that performs a control function.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The value returned by a command to its caller.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] The value is restricted to eight bits, so the maximum value is 255.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A unit of text that is the result of one of the shell expansions.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] After expansion, when executing a command, the resulting fields are used as the command name and arguments.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A string of characters used to identify a file.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A set of processes comprising a pipeline, and any processes descended from it, that are all in the same process group.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A mechanism by which users can selectively stop (suspend) and restart (resume) execution of processes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A character that, when unquoted, separates words.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A `word` consisting solely of letters, numbers, and underscores, and beginning with a letter or underscore.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] `Name`s are used as shell variable and function names.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A `control operator` or a `redirection operator`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] See Redirections, for a list of redirection operators.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Operators contain at least one unquoted `metacharacter`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A collection of related processes each having the same process group ID.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A unique identifier that represents a `process group` during its lifetime.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A `word` that has a special meaning to the shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Most reserved words introduce shell flow control constructs, such as `for` and `while`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A mechanism by which a process may be notified by the kernel of an event occurring in the system.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A shell builtin command that has been classified as special by the POSIX standard.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A sequence of characters considered a single unit by the shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] A sequence of characters treated as a unit by the shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p01] Words may not include unquoted `metacharacters`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Bash is an acronym for ‘Bourne-Again SHell’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The Bourne shell is the traditional Unix shell originally written by Stephen Bourne.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] All of the Bourne shell builtin commands are available in Bash, and the rules for evaluation and quoting are taken from the POSIX specification for the ‘standard’ Unix shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This chapter briefly summarizes the shell’s ‘building blocks’: commands, control structures, shell functions, shell *parameters*, shell expansions, *redirections*, which are a way to direct input and output from and to named files, and how the shell executes commands.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the shell reads input, it proceeds through a sequence of operations.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the input indicates the beginning of a comment, the shell ignores the comment symbol (‘#’), and the rest of that line.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Otherwise, roughly speaking, the shell reads its input and divides the input into words and operators, employing the quoting rules to select which meanings to assign various words and characters.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The following is a brief description of the shell’s operation when it reads and executes a command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Breaks the input into words and operators, obeying the quoting rules described in Quoting.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] These tokens are separated by `metacharacters`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This step performs alias expansion (see Aliases).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Parses the tokens into simple and compound commands (see Shell Commands).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Performs the various shell expansions (see Shell Expansions), breaking the expanded tokens into lists of filenames (see Filename Expansion) and commands and arguments.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Performs any necessary redirections (see Redirections) and removes the redirection operators and their operands from the argument list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Executes the command (see Executing Commands).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Optionally waits for the command to complete and collects its exit status (see Exit Status).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Quoting is used to remove the special meaning of certain characters or words to the shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Quoting can be used to disable special treatment for special characters, to prevent reserved words from being recognized as such, and to prevent parameter expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Each of the shell metacharacters (see Definitions) has special meaning to the shell and must be quoted if it is to represent itself.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the command history expansion facilities are being used (see History Expansion), the *history expansion* character, usually ‘!’, must be quoted to prevent history expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] See Bash History Facilities, for more details concerning history expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] There are four quoting mechanisms: the *escape character*, single quotes, double quotes, and dollar-single quotes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A non-quoted backslash ‘\’ is the Bash escape character.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] It preserves the literal value of the next character that follows, removing any special meaning it has, with the exception of `newline`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If a `\newline` pair appears, and the backslash itself is not quoted, the `\newline` is treated as a line continuation (that is, it is removed from the input stream and effectively ignored).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Enclosing characters in single quotes (‘'’) preserves the literal value of each character within the quotes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A single quote may not occur between single quotes, even when preceded by a backslash.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Enclosing characters in double quotes (‘"’) preserves the literal value of all characters within the quotes, with the exception of ‘$’, ‘`’, ‘\’, and, when history expansion is enabled, ‘!’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the shell is in POSIX mode (see Bash and POSIX), the ‘!’ has no special meaning within double quotes, even when history expansion is enabled.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The characters ‘$’ and ‘`’ retain their special meaning within double quotes (see Shell Expansions).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The backslash retains its special meaning only when followed by one of the following characters: ‘$’, ‘`’, ‘"’, ‘\’, or `newline`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Within double quotes, backslashes that are followed by one of these characters are removed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Backslashes preceding characters without a special meaning are left unmodified.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A double quote may be quoted within double quotes by preceding it with a backslash.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If enabled, history expansion will be performed unless an ‘!’ appearing in double quotes is escaped using a backslash.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The backslash preceding the ‘!’ is not removed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The special parameters ‘*’ and ‘@’ have special meaning when in double quotes (see Shell Parameter Expansion).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Character sequences of the form `$'*string*'` are treated as a special kind of single quotes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The sequence expands to *string*, with backslash-escaped characters in *string* replaced as specified by the ANSI C standard.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The eight-bit character whose value is the octal value *nnn* (one to three octal digits).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The eight-bit character whose value is the hexadecimal value *HH* (one or two hex digits).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The Unicode (ISO/IEC 10646) character whose value is the hexadecimal value *HHHH* (one to four hex digits).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The Unicode (ISO/IEC 10646) character whose value is the hexadecimal value *HHHHHHHH* (one to eight hex digits).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The expanded result is single-quoted, as if the dollar sign had not been present.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Prefixing a double-quoted string with a dollar sign (‘$’), such as `$"hello, world"`, causes the string to be translated according to the current locale.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The `gettext` infrastructure performs the lookup and translation, using the `LC_MESSAGES`, `TEXTDOMAINDIR`, and `TEXTDOMAIN` shell variables, as explained below.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] See the gettext documentation for additional details not covered here.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the current locale is `C` or `POSIX`, if there are no translations available, or if the string is not translated, the dollar sign is ignored, and the string is treated as double-quoted as described above.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Since this is a form of double quoting, the string remains double-quoted by default, whether or not it is translated and replaced.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the `noexpand_translation` option is enabled using the `shopt` builtin (see The Shopt Builtin), translated strings are single-quoted instead of double-quoted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The rest of this section is a brief overview of how you use gettext to create translations for strings in a shell script named *scriptname*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] There are more details in the gettext documentation.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] It’s just an arbitrary string that’s used to identify the files gettext needs, like a package or script name.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] It needs to be unique among all the message domains on systems where you install the translations, so gettext knows which translations correspond to your script.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] You’ll use the template file to create translations for each target language.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The template file conventionally has the suffix ‘.pot’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] You copy this template file to a separate file for each target language you want to support (called "PO" files, which use the suffix ‘.po’).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] PO files use various naming conventions, but when you are working to translate a template file into a particular language, you first copy the template file to a file whose name is the language you want to target, with the ‘.po’ suffix.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Ultimately, PO files are often named *domain*.po and installed in directories that contain multiple translation files for a particular language.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Whichever naming convention you choose, you will need to translate the strings in the PO files into the appropriate languages.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When you have the translations and PO files complete, you’ll use the gettext tools to produce what are called "MO" files, which are compiled versions of the PO files the gettext tools use to look up translations efficiently.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] MO files are also called "message catalog" files.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] You use the `msgfmt` program to do this.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Once you have the MO files, you decide where to install them and use the `TEXTDOMAINDIR` shell variable to tell the gettext tools where they are.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Make sure to use the same message domain to name the MO files as you did for the PO files when you install them.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Your users will use the `LANG` or `LC_MESSAGES` shell variables to select the desired language.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] You set the `TEXTDOMAIN` variable to the script’s message domain.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] As above, you use the message domain to name your translation files.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] You, or possibly your users, set the `TEXTDOMAINDIR` variable to the name of a directory where the message catalog files are stored.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If you install the message files into the system’s standard message catalog directory, you don’t need to worry about this variable.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The directory where the message catalog files are stored varies between systems.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Some use the message catalog selected by the `LC_MESSAGES` shell variable.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Others create the name of the message catalog from the value of the `TEXTDOMAIN` shell variable, possibly adding the ‘.mo’ suffix.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If you use the `TEXTDOMAIN` variable, you may need to set the `TEXTDOMAINDIR` variable to the location of the message catalog files, as above.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] It’s common to use both variables in this fashion: `$TEXTDOMAINDIR`/`$LC_MESSAGES`/LC_MESSAGES/`$TEXTDOMAIN`.mo.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A simple shell command such as `echo a b c` consists of the command itself followed by arguments, separated by spaces.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] More complex shell commands are composed of simple commands arranged together in a variety of ways: in a pipeline in which the output of one command becomes the input of a second, in a loop or conditional construct, or in some other grouping.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Reserved words are words that have special meaning to the shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] They are used to begin and end the shell’s compound commands.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] `in` is recognized as a reserved word if it is the third word of a `case` or `select` command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] `in` and `do` are recognized as reserved words if they are the third word in a `for` command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A simple command is the kind of command that’s executed most often.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] It’s just a sequence of words separated by `blank`s, terminated by one of the shell’s control operators (see Definitions).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The first word generally specifies a command to be executed, with the rest of the words being that command’s arguments.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return status (see Exit Status) of a simple command is its exit status as provided by the POSIX 1003.1 `waitpid` function, or 128+*n* if the command was terminated by signal *n*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A `pipeline` is a sequence of one or more commands separated by one of the control operators ‘|’ or ‘|&’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The output of each command in the pipeline is connected via a pipe to the input of the next command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] That is, each command reads the previous command’s output.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This connection is performed before any redirections specified by *command1*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If ‘|&’ is the pipeline operator, *command1*’s standard error, in addition to its standard output, is connected to *command2*’s standard input through the pipe; it is shorthand for `2>&1 |`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This implicit redirection of the standard error to the standard output is performed after any redirections specified by *command1*, consistent with that shorthand.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the reserved word `time` precedes the pipeline, Bash prints timing statistics for the pipeline once it finishes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The statistics currently consist of elapsed (wall-clock) time and user and system time consumed by the command’s execution.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The -p option changes the output format to that specified by POSIX.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the shell is in POSIX mode (see Bash and POSIX), it does not recognize `time` as a reserved word if the next token begins with a ‘-’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The value of the `TIMEFORMAT` variable is a format string that specifies how the timing information should be displayed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] See Bash Variables, for a description of the available formats.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Providing `time` as a reserved word permits the timing of shell builtins, shell functions, and pipelines.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] An external `time` command cannot time these easily.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the shell is in POSIX mode (see Bash and POSIX), you can use `time` by itself as a simple command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In this case, the shell displays the total user and system time consumed by the shell and its children.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The `TIMEFORMAT` variable specifies the format of the time information.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If a pipeline is not executed asynchronously (see Lists of Commands), the shell waits for all commands in the pipeline to complete.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Each command in a multi-command pipeline, where pipes are created, is executed in its own *subshell*, which is a separate process (see Command Execution Environment).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the `lastpipe` option is enabled using the `shopt` builtin (see The Shopt Builtin), and job control is not active, the last element of a pipeline may be run by the shell process.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The exit status of a pipeline is the exit status of the last command in the pipeline, unless the `pipefail` option is enabled (see The Set Builtin).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If `pipefail` is enabled, the pipeline’s return status is the value of the last (rightmost) command to exit with a non-zero status, or zero if all commands exit successfully.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the reserved word ‘!’ precedes the pipeline, the exit status is the logical negation of the exit status as described above.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If a pipeline is not executed asynchronously (see Lists of Commands), the shell waits for all commands in the pipeline to terminate before returning a value.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return status of an asynchronous pipeline is 0.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A `list` is a sequence of one or more pipelines separated by one of the operators ‘;’, ‘&’, ‘&&’, or ‘||’, and optionally terminated by one of ‘;’, ‘&’, or a `newline`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Of these list operators, ‘&&’ and ‘||’ have equal precedence, followed by ‘;’ and ‘&’, which have equal precedence.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A sequence of one or more newlines may appear in a `list` to delimit commands, equivalent to a semicolon.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If a command is terminated by the control operator ‘&’, the shell executes the command asynchronously in a subshell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This is known as executing the command in the *background*, and these are referred to as *asynchronous* commands.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The shell does not wait for the command to finish, and the return status is 0 (true).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When job control is not active (see Job Control), the standard input for asynchronous commands, in the absence of any explicit redirections, is redirected from `/dev/null`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Commands separated by a ‘;’ are executed sequentially; the shell waits for each command to terminate in turn.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return status is the exit status of the last command executed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] AND and OR lists are sequences of one or more pipelines separated by the control operators ‘&&’ and ‘||’, respectively.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] AND and OR lists are executed with left associativity.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return status of AND and OR lists is the exit status of the last command executed in the list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Compound commands are the shell programming language constructs.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Each construct begins with a reserved word or control operator and is terminated by a corresponding reserved word or operator.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Any redirections (see Redirections) associated with a compound command apply to all commands within that compound command unless explicitly overridden.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In most cases a list of commands in a compound command’s description may be separated from the rest of the command by one or more newlines, and may be followed by a newline in place of a semicolon.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Bash provides looping constructs, conditional commands, and mechanisms to group commands and execute them as a unit.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Bash supports the following looping constructs.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Note that wherever a ‘;’ appears in the description of a command’s syntax, it may be replaced with one or more newlines.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Execute *consequent-commands* as long as *test-commands* has an exit status which is not zero.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return status is the exit status of the last command executed in *consequent-commands*, or zero if none was executed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Execute *consequent-commands* as long as *test-commands* has an exit status of zero.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Expand *words* (see Shell Expansions), and then execute *commands* once for each word in the resultant list, with *name* bound to the current word.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If ‘in *words*’ is not present, the `for` command executes the *commands* once for each positional parameter that is set, as if ‘in "$@"’ had been specified (see Special Parameters).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return status is the exit status of the last command that executes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If there are no items in the expansion of *words*, no commands are executed, and the return status is zero.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] First, evaluate the arithmetic expression *expr1* according to the rules described below (see Shell Arithmetic).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Then, repeatedly evaluate the arithmetic expression *expr2* until it evaluates to zero.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Each time *expr2* evaluates to a non-zero value, execute *commands* and evaluate the arithmetic expression *expr3*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If any expression is omitted, it behaves as if it evaluates to 1.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return value is the exit status of the last command in *commands* that is executed, or non-zero if any of the expressions is invalid.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Use the `break` and `continue` builtins (see Bourne Shell Builtins) to control loop execution.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The *test-commands* list is executed, and if its return status is zero, the *consequent-commands* list is executed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If *test-commands* returns a non-zero status, each `elif` list is executed in turn, and if its exit status is zero, the corresponding *more-consequents* is executed and the command completes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If ‘else *alternate-consequents*’ is present, and the final command in the final `if` or `elif` clause has a non-zero exit status, then *alternate-consequents* is executed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return status is the exit status of the last command executed, or zero if no condition tested true.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] `case` will selectively execute the *command-list* corresponding to the first *pattern* that matches *word*, proceeding from the first pattern to the last.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The match is performed according to the rules described below in Pattern Matching.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the `nocasematch` shell option (see the description of `shopt` in The Shopt Builtin) is enabled, the match is performed without regard to the case of alphabetic characters.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The ‘|’ is used to separate multiple patterns in a pattern list, and the ‘)’ operator terminates the pattern list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A pattern list and an associated *command-list* is known as a *clause*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The *word* undergoes tilde expansion, parameter expansion, command substitution, process substitution, arithmetic expansion, and quote removal (see Shell Parameter Expansion) before the shell attempts to match the pattern.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Each *pattern* undergoes tilde expansion, parameter expansion, command substitution, arithmetic expansion, process substitution, and quote removal.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] There may be an arbitrary number of `case` clauses, each terminated by a ‘;;’, ‘;&’, or ‘;;&’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The first pattern that matches determines the command-list that is executed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] It’s a common idiom to use ‘*’ as the final pattern to define the default case, since that pattern will always match.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the ‘;;’ operator is used, the `case` command completes after the first pattern match.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Using ‘;&’ in place of ‘;;’ causes execution to continue with the *command-list* associated with the next clause, if any.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Using ‘;;&’ in place of ‘;;’ causes the shell to test the patterns in the next clause, if any, and execute any associated *command-list* if the match succeeds, continuing the case statement execution as if the pattern list had not matched.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return status is zero if no *pattern* matches.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Otherwise, the return status is the exit status of the last *command-list* executed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The `select` construct allows the easy generation of menus.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] First, expand the list of words following `in`, generating a list of items, and print the set of expanded words on the standard error stream, each preceded by a number.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the ‘in *words*’ is omitted, print the positional parameters, as if ‘in "$@"’ had been specified.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] `select` then displays the `PS3` prompt and reads a line from the standard input.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the line consists of a number corresponding to one of the displayed words, then `select` sets the value of *name* to that word.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the line is empty, `select` displays the words and prompt again.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If `EOF` is read, `select` completes and returns 1.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Any other value read causes *name* to be set to null.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The line read is saved in the variable `REPLY`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The *commands* are executed after each selection until a `break` command is executed, at which point the `select` command completes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Here is an example that allows the user to pick a filename from the current directory, and displays the name and index of the file selected.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The arithmetic *expression* is evaluated according to the rules described below (see Shell Arithmetic).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The *expression* undergoes the same expansions as if it were within double quotes, but unescaped double quote characters in *expression* are not treated specially and are removed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Since this can potentially result in empty strings, this command treats those as expressions that evaluate to 0.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the value of the expression is non-zero, the return status is 0; otherwise the return status is 1.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Evaluate the conditional expression *expression* and return a status of zero (true) or non-zero (false).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Expressions are composed of the primaries described below in Bash Conditional Expressions.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The words between the `[[` and `]]` do not undergo word splitting and filename expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The shell performs tilde expansion, parameter and variable expansion, arithmetic expansion, command substitution, process substitution, and quote removal on those words.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Conditional operators such as ‘-f’ must be unquoted to be recognized as primaries.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When used with `[[`, the ‘<’ and ‘>’ operators sort lexicographically using the current locale.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the ‘==’ and ‘!=’ operators are used, the string to the right of the operator is considered a pattern and matched according to the rules described below in Pattern Matching, as if the `extglob` shell option were enabled.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return value is 0 if the string matches (‘==’) or does not match (‘!=’) the pattern, and 1 otherwise.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If you quote any part of the pattern, using any of the shell’s quoting mechanisms, the quoted portion is matched literally.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This means every character in the quoted portion matches itself, instead of having any special pattern matching meaning.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] An additional binary operator, ‘=~’, is available, with the same precedence as ‘==’ and ‘!=’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When you use ‘=~’, the string to the right of the operator is considered a POSIX extended regular expression pattern and matched accordingly (using the POSIX `regcomp` and `regexec` interfaces usually described in *regex*(3)).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return value is 0 if the string matches the pattern, and 1 if it does not.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the regular expression is syntactically incorrect, the conditional expression returns 2.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] You can quote any part of the pattern to force the quoted portion to be matched literally instead of as a regular expression (see above).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the pattern is stored in a shell variable, quoting the variable expansion forces the entire pattern to be matched literally.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The match succeeds if the pattern matches any part of the string.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If you want to force the pattern to match the entire string, anchor the pattern using the ‘^’ and ‘$’ regular expression operators.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] That means values for `line` like ‘aab’, ‘ aaaaaab’, ‘xaby’, and ‘ ab’ will all match, as will a line containing a ‘b’ anywhere in its value.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If you want to match a character that’s special to the regular expression grammar (‘^$|[]()\.*+?’), it has to be quoted to remove its special meaning.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This means that in the pattern ‘xxx.txt’, the ‘.’ matches any character in the string (its usual regular expression meaning), but in the pattern ‘"xxx.txt"’, it can only match a literal ‘.’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Likewise, if you want to include a character in your pattern that has a special meaning to the regular expression grammar, you must make sure it’s not quoted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If you want to anchor a pattern at the beginning or end of the string, for instance, you cannot quote the ‘^’ or ‘$’ characters using any form of shell quoting.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] because in the second example the ‘^’ is quoted and doesn’t have its usual special meaning.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] It is sometimes difficult to specify a regular expression properly without using quotes, or to keep track of the quoting used by regular expressions while paying attention to shell quoting and the shell’s quote removal.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Storing the regular expression in a shell variable is often a useful way to avoid problems with quoting characters that are special to the shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Shell programmers should take special care with backslashes, since backslashes are used by both the shell and regular expressions to remove the special meaning from the following character.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This means that after the shell’s word expansions complete (see Shell Expansions), any backslashes remaining in parts of the pattern that were originally not quoted can remove the special meaning of pattern characters.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If any part of the pattern is quoted, the shell does its best to ensure that the regular expression treats those remaining backslashes as literal, if they appeared in a quoted portion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The first two matches will succeed, but the second two will not, because in the second two the backslash will be part of the pattern to be matched.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In the first two examples, the pattern passed to the regular expression parser is ‘\.’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The backslash removes the special meaning from ‘.’, so the literal ‘.’ matches.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In the second two examples, the pattern passed to the regular expression parser has the backslash quoted (e.g., ‘\\\.’), which will not match the string, since it does not contain a backslash.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the string in the first examples were anything other than ‘.’, say ‘a’, the pattern would not match, because the quoted ‘.’ in the pattern loses its special meaning of matching any single character.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Bracket expressions in regular expressions can be sources of errors as well, since characters that are normally special in regular expressions lose their special meanings between brackets.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] However, you can use bracket expressions to match special pattern characters without quoting them, so they are sometimes useful for this purpose.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The shell performs any word expansions before passing the pattern to the regular expression functions, so you can assume that the shell’s quoting takes precedence.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] As noted above, the regular expression parser will interpret any unquoted backslashes remaining in the pattern after shell expansion according to its own rules.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The intention is to avoid making shell programmers quote things twice as much as possible, so shell quoting should be sufficient to quote special pattern characters where that’s necessary.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The array variable `BASH_REMATCH` records which parts of the string matched the pattern.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The element of `BASH_REMATCH` with index 0 contains the portion of the string matching the entire regular expression.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Substrings matched by parenthesized subexpressions within the regular expression are saved in the remaining `BASH_REMATCH` indices.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The element of `BASH_REMATCH` with index *n* is the portion of the string matching the *n*th parenthesized subexpression.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Bash sets `BASH_REMATCH` in the global scope; declaring it as a local variable will lead to unexpected results.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This may be used to override the normal precedence of operators.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] True if both *expression1* and *expression2* are true.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] True if either *expression1* or *expression2* is true.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The `&&` and `||` operators do not evaluate *expression2* if the value of *expression1* is sufficient to determine the return value of the entire conditional expression.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Bash provides two ways to group a list of commands to be executed as a unit.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When commands are grouped, redirections may be applied to the entire command list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] For example, the output of all the commands in the list may be redirected to a single stream.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Placing a list of commands between parentheses forces the shell to create a subshell (see Command Execution Environment), and each of the commands in *list* is executed in that subshell environment.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Since the *list* is executed in a subshell, variable assignments do not remain in effect after the subshell completes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Placing a list of commands between curly braces causes the list to be executed in the current shell environment.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The semicolon (or newline) following *list* is required.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In addition to the creation of a subshell, there is a subtle difference between these two constructs due to historical reasons.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The braces are reserved words, so they must be separated from the *list* by `blank`s or other shell metacharacters.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The parentheses are operators, and are recognized as separate tokens by the shell even if they are not separated from the *list* by whitespace.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The exit status of both of these constructs is the exit status of *list*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A `coprocess` is a shell command preceded by the `coproc` reserved word.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A coprocess is executed asynchronously in a subshell, as if the command had been terminated with the ‘&’ control operator, with a two-way pipe established between the executing shell and the coprocess.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] *command* may be either a simple command (see Simple Commands) or a compound command (see Compound Commands).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If *NAME* is not supplied, the default name is `COPROC`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This form is preferred because simple commands result in the coprocess always being named `COPROC`, and it is simpler to use and more complete than the other compound commands.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If *command* is a compound command, *NAME* is optional.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The word following `coproc` determines whether that word is interpreted as a variable name: it is interpreted as *NAME* if it is not a reserved word that introduces a compound command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If *command* is a simple command, *NAME* is not allowed; this is to avoid confusion between *NAME* and the first word of the simple command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the coprocess is executed, the shell creates an array variable (see Arrays) named *NAME* in the context of the executing shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The standard output of *command* is connected via a pipe to a file descriptor in the executing shell, and that file descriptor is assigned to *NAME*[0].
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The standard input of *command* is connected via a pipe to a file descriptor in the executing shell, and that file descriptor is assigned to *NAME*[1].
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This pipe is established before any redirections specified by the command (see Redirections).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The file descriptors can be utilized as arguments to shell commands and redirections using standard word expansions.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Other than those created to execute command and process substitutions, the file descriptors are not available in subshells.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The process ID of the shell spawned to execute the coprocess is available as the value of the variable `*NAME*_PID`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The `wait` builtin may be used to wait for the coprocess to terminate.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Since the coprocess is created as an asynchronous command, the `coproc` command always returns success.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The return status of a coprocess is the exit status of *command*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] There are ways to run commands in parallel that are not built into Bash.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] GNU Parallel, as its name suggests, can be used to build and run commands in parallel.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] You may run the same command with different arguments, whether they are filenames, usernames, hostnames, or lines read from files.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] GNU Parallel provides shorthand references to many of the most common operations (input lines, various portions of the input line, different ways to specify the input source, and so on).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Parallel can replace `xargs` or feed commands from its input sources to several different instances of Bash.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] For a complete description, refer to the GNU Parallel documentation, which is available at https://www.gnu.org/software/parallel/parallel_tutorial.html.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Shell functions are a way to group commands for later execution using a single name for the group.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] They are executed just like a "regular" simple command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the name of a shell function is used as a simple command name, the shell executes the list of commands associated with that function name.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Shell functions are executed in the current shell context; there is no new process created to interpret them.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This defines a shell function named *fname*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The reserved word `function` is optional.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the `function` reserved word is supplied, the parentheses are optional.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The *body* of the function is the compound command *compound-command* (see Compound Commands).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] That command is usually a *list* enclosed between { and }, but may be any compound command listed above.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the `function` reserved word is used, but the parentheses are not supplied, the braces are recommended.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the shell is in POSIX mode (see Bash and POSIX), *fname* must be a valid shell name and may not be the same as one of the special builtins (see Special Builtins).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When not in POSIX mode, a function name can be any unquoted shell word that does not contain ‘$’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Any redirections (see Redirections) associated with the shell function are performed when the function is executed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Function definitions are deleted using the -f option to the `unset` builtin (see Bourne Shell Builtins).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The exit status of a function definition is zero unless a syntax error occurs or a readonly function with the same name already exists.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When executed, the exit status of a function is the exit status of the last command executed in the body.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Note that for historical reasons, in the most common usage the curly braces that surround the body of the function must be separated from the body by `blank`s or newlines.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This is because the braces are reserved words and are only recognized as such when they are separated from the command list by whitespace or another shell metacharacter.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When using the braces, the *list* must be terminated by a semicolon, a ‘&’, or a newline.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When a function is executed, the arguments to the function become the positional parameters during its execution (see Positional Parameters).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The special parameter ‘#’ that expands to the number of positional parameters is updated to reflect the new set of positional parameters.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The first element of the `FUNCNAME` variable is set to the name of the function while the function is executing.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] See Bourne Shell Builtins, for the description of the `trap` builtin.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The `FUNCNEST` variable, if set to a numeric value greater than 0, defines a maximum function nesting level.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Function invocations that exceed the limit cause the entire command to abort.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the builtin command `return` is executed in a function, the function completes and execution resumes with the next command after the function call.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Any command associated with the `RETURN` trap is executed before execution resumes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When a function completes, the values of the positional parameters and the special parameter ‘#’ are restored to the values they had prior to the function’s execution.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If `return` is supplied a numeric argument, that is the function’s return status; otherwise the function’s return status is the exit status of the last command executed before the `return`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Variables local to the function are declared with the `local` builtin (*local variables*).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Ordinarily, variables and their values are shared between a function and its caller.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] These variables are visible only to the function and the commands it invokes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This is particularly important when a shell function calls other functions.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In the following description, the *current scope* is a currently- executing function.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Previous scopes consist of that function’s caller and so on, back to the "global" scope, where the shell is not executing any shell function.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A local variable at the current local scope is a variable declared using the `local` or `declare` builtins in the function that is currently executing.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Local variables "shadow" variables with the same name declared at previous scopes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] For instance, a local variable declared in a function hides variables with the same name declared at previous scopes, including global variables: references and assignments refer to the local variable, leaving the variables at previous scopes unmodified.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the function returns, the global variable is once again visible.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The shell uses *dynamic scoping* to control a variable’s visibility within functions.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] With dynamic scoping, visible variables and their values are a result of the sequence of function calls that caused execution to reach the current function.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The value of a variable that a function sees depends on its value within its caller, if any, whether that caller is the global scope or another shell function.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This is also the value that a local variable declaration shadows, and the value that is restored when the function returns.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] For example, if a variable `var` is declared as local in function `func1`, and `func1` calls another function `func2`, references to `var` made from within `func2` resolve to the local variable `var` from `func1`, shadowing any global variable named `var`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The following script demonstrates this behavior.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The `unset` builtin also acts using the same dynamic scope: if a variable is local to the current scope, `unset` unsets it; otherwise the unset will refer to the variable found in any calling scope as described above.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If a variable at the current local scope is unset, it remains so (appearing as unset) until it is reset in that scope or until the function returns.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Once the function returns, any instance of the variable at a previous scope becomes visible.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the unset acts on a variable at a previous scope, any instance of a variable with that name that had been shadowed becomes visible (see below how the `localvar_unset` shell option changes this behavior).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The -f option to the `declare` (`typeset`) builtin command (see Bash Builtin Commands) lists function names and definitions.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The -F option to `declare` or `typeset` lists the function names only (and optionally the source file and line number, if the `extdebug` shell option is enabled).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Functions may be exported so that child shell processes (those created when executing a separate shell invocation) automatically have them defined with the -f option to the `export` builtin (see Bourne Shell Builtins).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The -f option to the `unset` builtin (see Bourne Shell Builtins) deletes a function definition.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The `FUNCNEST` variable may be used to limit the depth of the function call stack and restrict the number of function invocations.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] By default, Bash places no limit on the number of recursive calls.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A *parameter* is an entity that stores values.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] It can be a `name`, a number, or one of the special characters listed below.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A *variable* is a parameter denoted by a `name`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A variable has a `value` and zero or more `attributes`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Attributes are assigned using the `declare` builtin command (see the description of the `declare` builtin in Bash Builtin Commands).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The `export` and `readonly` builtins assign specific attributes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A parameter is set if it has been assigned a value.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Once a variable is set, it may be unset only by using the `unset` builtin command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If *value* is not given, the variable is assigned the null string.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] All *value*s undergo tilde expansion, parameter and variable expansion, command substitution, arithmetic expansion, and quote removal (see Shell Parameter Expansion).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the variable has its `integer` attribute set, then *value* is evaluated as an arithmetic expression even if the `$((…))` expansion is not used (see Arithmetic Expansion).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Word splitting and filename expansion are not performed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Assignment statements may also appear as arguments to the `alias`, `declare`, `typeset`, `export`, `readonly`, and `local` builtin commands (*declaration commands*).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When in POSIX mode (see Bash and POSIX), these builtins may appear in a command after one or more instances of the `command` builtin and retain these assignment statement properties.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In the context where an assignment statement is assigning a value to a shell variable or array index (see Arrays), the ‘+=’ operator appends to or adds to the variable’s previous value.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This includes arguments to declaration commands such as `declare` that accept assignment statements.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When ‘+=’ is applied to a variable for which the `integer` attribute has been set, the variable’s current value and *value* are each evaluated as arithmetic expressions, and the sum of the results is assigned as the variable’s value.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The current value is usually an integer constant, but may be an expression.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When applied to a string-valued variable, *value* is expanded and appended to the variable’s value.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A variable can be assigned the `nameref` attribute using the -n option to the `declare` or `local` builtin commands (see Bash Builtin Commands) to create a *nameref*, or a reference to another variable.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This allows variables to be manipulated indirectly.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Whenever the nameref variable is referenced, assigned to, unset, or has its attributes modified (other than using or changing the nameref attribute itself), the operation is actually performed on the variable specified by the nameref variable’s value.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A nameref is commonly used within shell functions to refer to a variable whose name is passed as an argument to the function.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] inside the function creates a local nameref variable `ref` whose value is the variable name passed as the first argument.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] References and assignments to `ref`, and changes to its attributes, are treated as references, assignments, and attribute modifications to the variable whose name was passed as `$1`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the control variable in a `for` loop has the nameref attribute, the list of words can be a list of shell variables, and a name reference is established for each word in the list, in turn, when the loop is executed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Array variables cannot be given the nameref attribute.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] However, nameref variables can reference array variables and subscripted array variables.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Namerefs can be unset using the -n option to the `unset` builtin (see Bourne Shell Builtins).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Otherwise, if `unset` is executed with the name of a nameref variable as an argument, the variable referenced by the nameref variable is unset.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the shell starts, it reads its environment and creates a shell variable from each environment variable that has a valid name, as described below (see Environment).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A *positional parameter* is a parameter denoted by one or more digits, other than the single digit `0`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Positional parameters are assigned from the shell’s arguments when it is invoked, and may be reassigned using the `set` builtin command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Positional parameter `N` may be referenced as `${N}`, or as `$N` when `N` consists of a single digit.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Positional parameters may not be assigned to with assignment statements.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The `set` and `shift` builtins are used to set and unset them (see Shell Builtin Commands).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The positional parameters are temporarily replaced when a shell function is executed (see Shell Functions).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When a positional parameter consisting of more than a single digit is expanded, it must be enclosed in braces.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Without braces, a digit following ‘$’ can only refer to one of the first nine positional parameters ($1\-$9) or the special parameter $0 (see below).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The shell treats several parameters specially.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] These parameters may only be referenced; assignment to them is not allowed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Special parameters are denoted by one of the following characters.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] ($*) Expands to the positional parameters, starting from one.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the expansion is not within double quotes, each positional parameter expands to a separate word.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In contexts where word expansions are performed, those words are subject to further word splitting and filename expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the expansion occurs within double quotes, it expands to a single word with the value of each parameter separated by the first character of the `IFS` variable.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] That is, `"$*"` is equivalent to `"$1*c*$2*c*…"`, where *c* is the first character of the value of the `IFS` variable.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If `IFS` is unset, the parameters are separated by spaces.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If `IFS` is null, the parameters are joined without intervening separators.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] ($@) Expands to the positional parameters, starting from one.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In contexts where word splitting is performed, this expands each positional parameter to a separate word; if not within double quotes, these words are subject to word splitting.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In contexts where word splitting is not performed, such as the value portion of an assignment statement, this expands to a single word with each positional parameter separated by a space.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the expansion occurs within double quotes, and word splitting is performed, each parameter expands to a separate word.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the double-quoted expansion occurs within a word, the expansion of the first parameter is joined with the expansion of the beginning part of the original word, and the expansion of the last parameter is joined with the expansion of the last part of the original word.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When there are no positional parameters, `"$@"` and `$@` expand to nothing (i.e., they are removed).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] ($#) Expands to the number of positional parameters in decimal.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] ($?) Expands to the exit status of the most recently executed command.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] ($-, a hyphen.) Expands to the current option flags as specified upon invocation, by the `set` builtin command, or those set by the shell itself (such as the -i option).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] ($$) Expands to the process ID of the shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] In a subshell, it expands to the process ID of the invoking shell, not the subshell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] ($!) Expands to the process ID of the job most recently placed into the background, whether executed as an asynchronous command or using the `bg` builtin (see Job Control Builtins).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] ($0) Expands to the name of the shell or shell script.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If Bash is invoked with a file of commands (see Shell Scripts), `$0` is set to the name of that file.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If Bash is started with the -c option (see Invoking Bash), then `$0` is set to the first argument after the string to be executed, if one is present.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Otherwise, it is set to the filename used to invoke Bash, as given by argument zero.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Expansion is performed on the command line after it has been split into `token`s.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The order of expansions is: brace expansion; tilde expansion, parameter and variable expansion, arithmetic expansion, and command substitution (done in a left-to-right fashion); word splitting; filename expansion; and quote removal.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] On systems that can support it, there is an additional expansion available: *process substitution*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This is performed at the same time as tilde, parameter, variable, and arithmetic expansion and command substitution.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Only brace expansion, word splitting, and filename expansion can increase the number of words of the expansion; other expansions expand a single word to a single word.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The only exceptions to this are the expansions of `"$@"` and `$*` (see Special Parameters), and `"${*name*[@]}"` and `${*name*[*]}` (see Arrays).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Brace expansion is a mechanism to generate arbitrary strings sharing a common prefix and suffix, either of which can be empty.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] This mechanism is similar to *filename expansion* (see Filename Expansion), but the filenames generated need not exist.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Patterns to be brace expanded are formed from an optional *preamble*, followed by either a series of comma-separated strings or a sequence expression between a pair of braces, followed by an optional *postscript*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The preamble is prefixed to each string contained within the braces, and the postscript is then appended to each resulting string, expanding left to right.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The results of each expanded string are not sorted; brace expansion preserves left to right order.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A sequence expression takes the form `*x*..*y*[..*incr*]`, where *x* and *y* are either integers or letters, and *incr*, an optional increment, is an integer.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When integers are supplied, the expression expands to each number between *x* and *y*, inclusive.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If either *x* or *y* begins with a zero, each generated term will contain the same number of digits, zero-padding where necessary.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When letters are supplied, the expression expands to each character lexicographically between *x* and *y*, inclusive, using the C locale.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Note that both *x* and *y* must be of the same type (integer or letter).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] When the increment is supplied, it is used as the difference between each term.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The default increment is 1 or -1 as appropriate.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Brace expansion is performed before any other expansions, and any characters special to other expansions are preserved in the result.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Bash does not apply any syntactic interpretation to the context of the expansion or the text between the braces.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A correctly-formed brace expansion must contain unquoted opening and closing braces, and at least one unquoted comma or a valid sequence expression.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Any incorrectly formed brace expansion is left unchanged.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] A ‘{’ or ‘,’ may be quoted with a backslash to prevent its being considered part of a brace expression.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] To avoid conflicts with parameter expansion, the string ‘${’ is not considered eligible for brace expansion, and inhibits brace expansion until the closing ‘}’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Brace expansion introduces a slight incompatibility with historical versions of `sh`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] `sh` does not treat opening or closing braces specially when they appear as part of a word, and preserves them in the output.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Bash removes braces from words as a consequence of brace expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] For example, a word entered to `sh` as ‘file{1,2}’ appears identically in the output.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Bash outputs that word as ‘file1 file2’ after brace expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Start Bash with the +B option or disable brace expansion with the +B option to the `set` command (see Shell Builtin Commands) for strict `sh` compatibility.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If a word begins with an unquoted tilde character (‘~’), all of the characters up to the first unquoted slash (or all characters, if there is no unquoted slash) are considered a *tilde-prefix*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If none of the characters in the tilde-prefix are quoted, the characters in the tilde-prefix following the tilde are treated as a possible *login name*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If this login name is the null string, the tilde is replaced with the value of the `HOME` shell variable.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If `HOME` is unset, the tilde expands to the home directory of the user executing the shell instead.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Otherwise, the tilde-prefix is replaced with the home directory associated with the specified login name.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the tilde-prefix is ‘~+’, the value of the shell variable `PWD` replaces the tilde-prefix.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the tilde-prefix is ‘~-’, the shell substitutes the value of the shell variable `OLDPWD`, if it is set.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the tilde-prefix, sans the tilde, consists of a number without a leading ‘+’ or ‘-’, tilde expansion assumes ‘+’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The results of tilde expansion are treated as if they were quoted, so the replacement is not subject to word splitting and filename expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] If the login name is invalid, or the tilde expansion fails, the tilde-prefix is left unchanged.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Bash checks each variable assignment for unquoted tilde-prefixes immediately following a ‘:’ or the first ‘=’, and performs tilde expansion in these cases.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] Consequently, one may use filenames with tildes in assignments to `PATH`, `MAILPATH`, and `CDPATH`, and the shell assigns the expanded value.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The directory or file `foo` in the home directory of the user `fred`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p02] The string that would be displayed by ‘dirs +*N*’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The string that would be displayed by ‘dirs -*N*’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Bash also performs tilde expansion on words satisfying the conditions of variable assignments (see Shell Parameters) when they appear as arguments to simple commands.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Bash does not do this, except for the declaration commands listed above, when in POSIX mode.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The ‘$’ character introduces parameter expansion, command substitution, or arithmetic expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The parameter name or symbol to be expanded may be enclosed in braces, which are optional but serve to protect the variable to be expanded from characters immediately following it which could be interpreted as part of the name.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] For example, if the first positional parameter has the value ‘a’, then `${11}` expands to the value of the eleventh positional parameter, while `$11` expands to ‘a1’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] When braces are used, the matching ending brace is the first ‘}’ not escaped by a backslash or within a quoted string, and not within an embedded arithmetic expansion, command substitution, or parameter expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The basic form of parameter expansion is ${*parameter*}, which substitutes the value of *parameter*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The *parameter* is a shell parameter as described above (see Shell Parameters) or an array reference (see Arrays).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The braces are required when *parameter* is a positional parameter with more than one digit, or when *parameter* is followed by a character that is not to be interpreted as part of its name.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If the first character of *parameter* is an exclamation point (!), and *parameter* is not a nameref, it introduces a level of indirection.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Bash uses the value formed by expanding the rest of *parameter* as the new *parameter*; this new parameter is then expanded and that value is used in the rest of the expansion, rather than the expansion of the original *parameter*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The value is subject to tilde expansion, parameter expansion, command substitution, and arithmetic expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is a nameref, this expands to the name of the variable referenced by *parameter* instead of performing the complete indirect expansion, for compatibility.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The exceptions to this are the expansions of ${!*prefix**} and ${!*name*[@]} described below.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The exclamation point must immediately follow the left brace in order to introduce indirection.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] In each of the cases below, *word* is subject to tilde expansion, parameter expansion, command substitution, and arithmetic expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] When not performing substring expansion, using the forms described below (e.g., ‘:-’), Bash tests for a parameter that is unset or null.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Omitting the colon results in a test only for a parameter that is unset.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Put another way, if the colon is included, the operator tests for both *parameter*’s existence and that its value is not null; if the colon is omitted, the operator tests only for existence.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is unset or null, the expansion of *word* is substituted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Otherwise, the value of *parameter* is substituted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is unset or null, the expansion of *word* is assigned to *parameter*, and the result of the expansion is the final value of *parameter*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Positional parameters and special parameters may not be assigned in this way.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is null or unset, the shell writes the expansion of *word* (or a message to that effect if *word* is not present) to the standard error and, if it is not interactive, exits with a non-zero status.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] An interactive shell does not exit, but does not execute the command associated with the expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is null or unset, nothing is substituted, otherwise the expansion of *word* is substituted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] This is referred to as Substring Expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] It expands to up to *length* characters of the value of *parameter* starting at the character specified by *offset*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is ‘@’ or ‘*’, an indexed array subscripted by ‘@’ or ‘*’, or an associative array name, the results differ as described below.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If :*length* is omitted (the first form above), this expands to the substring of the value of *parameter* starting at the character specified by *offset* and extending to the end of the value.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *offset* is omitted, it is treated as 0.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *length* is omitted, but the colon after *offset* is present, it is treated as 0.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] *length* and *offset* are arithmetic expressions (see Shell Arithmetic).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *offset* evaluates to a number less than zero, the value is used as an offset in characters from the end of the value of *parameter*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *length* evaluates to a number less than zero, it is interpreted as an offset in characters from the end of the value of *parameter* rather than a number of characters, and the expansion is the characters between *offset* and that result.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Note that a negative offset must be separated from the colon by at least one space to avoid being confused with the ‘:-’ expansion.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is ‘@’ or ‘*’, the result is *length* positional parameters beginning at *offset*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] A negative *offset* is taken relative to one greater than the greatest positional parameter, so an offset of -1 evaluates to the last positional parameter (or 0 if there are no positional parameters).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] It is an expansion error if *length* evaluates to a number less than zero.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is an indexed array name subscripted by ‘@’ or ‘*’, the result is the *length* members of the array beginning with `${*parameter*[*offset*]}`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] A negative *offset* is taken relative to one greater than the maximum index of the specified array.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Substring expansion applied to an associative array produces undefined results.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Substring indexing is zero-based unless the positional parameters are used, in which case the indexing starts at 1 by default.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *offset* is 0, and the positional parameters are used, `$0` is prefixed to the list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Expands to the names of variables whose names begin with *prefix*, separated by the first character of the `IFS` special variable.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] When ‘@’ is used and the expansion appears within double quotes, each variable name expands to a separate word.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *name* is an array variable, expands to the list of array indices (keys) assigned in *name*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *name* is not an array, expands to 0 if *name* is set and null otherwise.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] When ‘@’ is used and the expansion appears within double quotes, each key expands to a separate word.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Substitutes the length in characters of the value of *parameter*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is ‘*’ or ‘@’, the value substituted is the number of positional parameters.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is an array name subscripted by ‘*’ or ‘@’, the value substituted is the number of elements in the array.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is an indexed array name subscripted by a negative number, that number is interpreted as relative to one greater than the maximum index of *parameter*, so negative indices count back from the end of the array, and an index of -1 references the last element.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The *word* is expanded to produce a pattern and matched against the expanded value of *parameter* according to the rules described below (see Pattern Matching).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If the pattern matches the beginning of the expanded value of *parameter*, then the result of the expansion is the expanded value of *parameter* with the shortest matching pattern (the ‘#’ case) or the longest matching pattern (the ‘##’ case) deleted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is ‘@’ or ‘*’, the pattern removal operation is applied to each positional parameter in turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is an array variable subscripted with ‘@’ or ‘*’, the pattern removal operation is applied to each member of the array in turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If the pattern matches a trailing portion of the expanded value of *parameter*, then the result of the expansion is the value of *parameter* with the shortest matching pattern (the ‘%’ case) or the longest matching pattern (the ‘%%’ case) deleted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The *pattern* is expanded to produce a pattern and matched against the expanded value of *parameter* as described below (see Pattern Matching).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The longest match of *pattern* in the expanded value is replaced with *string*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] *string* undergoes tilde expansion, parameter and variable expansion, arithmetic expansion, command and process substitution, and quote removal.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] In the first form above, only the first match is replaced.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If there are two slashes separating *parameter* and *pattern* (the second form above), all matches of *pattern* are replaced with *string*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *pattern* is preceded by ‘#’ (the third form above), it must match at the beginning of the expanded value of *parameter*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *pattern* is preceded by ‘%’ (the fourth form above), it must match at the end of the expanded value of *parameter*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If the expansion of *string* is null, matches of *pattern* are deleted and the ‘/’ following *pattern* may be omitted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If the `patsub_replacement` shell option is enabled using `shopt` (see The Shopt Builtin), any unquoted instances of ‘&’ in *string* are replaced with the matching portion of *pattern*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] This is intended to duplicate a common `sed` idiom.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Quoting any part of *string* inhibits replacement in the expansion of the quoted portion, including replacement strings stored in shell variables.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Backslash escapes ‘&’ in *string*; the backslash is removed in order to permit a literal ‘&’ in the replacement string.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Users should take care if *string* is double-quoted to avoid unwanted interactions between the backslash and double-quoting, since backslash has special meaning within double quotes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Pattern substitution performs the check for unquoted ‘&’ after expanding *string*, so users should ensure to properly quote any occurrences of ‘&’ they want to be taken literally in the replacement and ensure any instances of ‘&’ they want to be replaced are unquoted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Like the pattern removal operators, double quotes surrounding the replacement string quote the expanded characters, while double quotes enclosing the entire parameter substitution do not, since the expansion is performed in a context that doesn’t take any enclosing double quotes into account.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Since backslash can escape ‘&’, it can also escape a backslash in the replacement string.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] It should rarely be necessary to enclose only *string* in double quotes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is ‘@’ or ‘*’, the substitution operation is applied to each positional parameter in turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is an array variable subscripted with ‘@’ or ‘*’, the substitution operation is applied to each member of the array in turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] This expansion modifies the case of alphabetic characters in *parameter*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] First, the *pattern* is expanded to produce a pattern as described below in Pattern Matching.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] `Bash` then examines characters in the expanded value of *parameter* against *pattern* as described below.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If a character matches the pattern, its case is converted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The pattern should not attempt to match more than one character.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Using ‘^’ converts lowercase letters matching *pattern* to uppercase; ‘,’ converts matching uppercase letters to lowercase.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The ‘^’ and ‘,’ variants examine the first character in the expanded value and convert its case if it matches *pattern*; the ‘^^’ and ‘,,’ variants examine all characters in the expanded value and convert each one that matches *pattern*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *pattern* is omitted, it is treated like a ‘?’, which matches every character.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is ‘@’ or ‘*’, the case modification operation is applied to each positional parameter in turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is an array variable subscripted with ‘@’ or ‘*’, the case modification operation is applied to each member of the array in turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The expansion is either a transformation of the value of *parameter* or information about *parameter* itself, depending on the value of *operator*.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The expansion is a string that is the value of *parameter* with lowercase alphabetic characters converted to uppercase.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The expansion is a string that is the value of *parameter* with the first character converted to uppercase, if it is alphabetic.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The expansion is a string that is the value of *parameter* with uppercase alphabetic characters converted to lowercase.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The expansion is a string that is the value of *parameter* quoted in a format that can be reused as input.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The expansion is a string that is the value of *parameter* with backslash escape sequences expanded as with the `$'…'` quoting mechanism.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The expansion is a string that is the result of expanding the value of *parameter* as if it were a prompt string (see Controlling the Prompt).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The expansion is a string in the form of an assignment statement or `declare` command that, if evaluated, recreates *parameter* with its attributes and value.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Produces a possibly-quoted version of the value of *parameter*, except that it prints the values of indexed and associative arrays as a sequence of quoted key-value pairs (see Arrays).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The keys and values are quoted in a format that can be reused as input.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The expansion is a string consisting of flag values representing *parameter*’s attributes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Like the ‘K’ transformation, but expands the keys and values of indexed and associative arrays to separate words after word splitting.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is ‘@’ or ‘*’, the operation is applied to each positional parameter in turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If *parameter* is an array variable subscripted with ‘@’ or ‘*’, the operation is applied to each member of the array in turn, and the expansion is the resultant list.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The result of the expansion is subject to word splitting and filename expansion as described below.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Command substitution allows the output of a command to replace the command itself.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Bash performs command substitution by executing *command* in a subshell environment and replacing the command substitution with the standard output of the command, with any trailing newlines deleted.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Embedded newlines are not deleted, but they may be removed during word splitting.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The command substitution `$(cat *file*)` can be replaced by the equivalent but faster `$(< *file*)`.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] With the old-style backquote form of substitution, backslash retains its literal meaning except when followed by ‘$’, ‘`’, or ‘\’.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The first backquote not preceded by a backslash terminates the command substitution.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] When using the `$(*command*)` form, all characters between the parentheses make up the command; none are treated specially.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] which executes *command* in the current execution environment and captures its output, again with trailing newlines removed.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The character *c* following the open brace must be a space, tab, newline, or ‘|’, and the close brace must be in a position where a reserved word may appear (i.e., preceded by a command terminator such as semicolon).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Bash allows the close brace to be joined to the remaining characters in the word without being followed by a shell metacharacter as a reserved word would usually require.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Any side effects of *command* take effect immediately in the current execution environment and persist in the current environment after the command completes (e.g., the `exit` builtin exits the shell).
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If the first character following the open brace is a ‘|’, the construct expands to the value of the `REPLY` shell variable after *command* executes, without removing any trailing newlines, and the standard output of *command* remains the same as in the calling shell.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Bash creates `REPLY` as an initially-unset local variable when *command* executes, and restores `REPLY` to the value it had before the command substitution after *command* completes, as with any local variable.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] and restores `REPLY` to the value it had before the command substitution.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] To nest when using the backquoted form, escape the inner backquotes with backslashes.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] If the substitution appears within double quotes, Bash does not perform word splitting and filename expansion on the results.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Arithmetic expansion evaluates an arithmetic expression and substitutes the result.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] All tokens in the expression undergo parameter and variable expansion, command substitution, and quote removal.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] The result is treated as the arithmetic expression to be evaluated.
[src:shell-linux/manual-bash-p03] Since the way Bash handles double quotes can potentially result in empty strings, arithmetic expansion treats those as expressions that evaluate to 0.
